South Korean President Roh Moo-Hyun called for an investigation into illegal recordings of conversations between the ambassador to the US and a Samsung executive in 1997.
The scandal involved alleged slush fund payments to politicians.
The National Intelligence Service was asked to conduct a thorough probe.
Ambassador Hong Seok-Hyun offered to resign amid suspicions of being a go-between for Samsung and politicians.
The wiretapping scandal led to the arrest of a former NIS official.
President Roh accepted the ambassador's resignation, acknowledging the impact on US cooperation regarding North Korea's nuclear program.
